INSERT INTO `omeka_exhibit_page_blocks` VALUES (1,9,'gallery',NULL,NULL,1),(2,11,'gallery',NULL,NULL,1),(3,15,'text',NULL,'',1),(4,17,'gallery',NULL,NULL,1),(5,18,'gallery',NULL,NULL,2),(6,18,'text',NULL,'<p><strong>DISCUSSIONS</strong><strong> | Amazing Stories (1927- )<br /></strong></p>\n<p>Hugo Gernsback\'s <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">Amazing Stories</span> was the first dedicated English-language science fiction magazine, and \"Discussions\" was the first fan letter column. Making its first appearance in the January 1927 issue, \"Discussions\" hosted early contacts and interchanges between the first SF fans.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/items/browse?search=&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Belement_id%5D=114&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Btype%5D=contains&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Bterms%5D=amazing&amp;range=&amp;collection=24&amp;type=&amp;user=&amp;tags=&amp;public=&amp;featured=&amp;exhibit=&amp;submit_search=Search\" target=\"_blank\">All available letters</a></p>\n<p>Â </p>',1),(7,19,'text',NULL,'<p>While a selection of letters is presented for each publication, the complete file of digitized material is available through the search interface. <a href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/items/search\" target=\"_blank\">Advanced search</a> provides full-text searching of letters, and a variety of faceted searches, including: date, author, subject, location, and relationship to other letters. Ex: for Amazing Stories, <a href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/items/browse?search=&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Belement_id%5D=92&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Btype%5D=contains&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Bterms%5D=1927&amp;range=&amp;collection=24&amp;type=&amp;user=&amp;tags=&amp;public=&amp;featured=&amp;exhibit=&amp;submit_search=Search+for+items\" target=\"_blank\">1927</a> or <a href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/items/browse?search=&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Belement_id%5D=49&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Btype%5D=contains&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Bterms%5D=verne&amp;range=&amp;collection=24&amp;type=&amp;user=&amp;tags=&amp;public=&amp;featured=&amp;exhibit=&amp;submit_search=Search+for+items\" target=\"_blank\">Jules Verne</a> or <a href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/items/browse?search=&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Belement_id%5D=109&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Btype%5D=is+not+empty&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Bterms%5D=&amp;range=&amp;collection=24&amp;type=&amp;user=&amp;tags=&amp;public=&amp;featured=&amp;exhibit=&amp;submit_search=Search+for+items\" target=\"_blank\">letters referencing other letters</a> or <a href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/items/browse?search=&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Belement_id%5D=105&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Btype%5D=is+not+empty&amp;advanced%5B0%5D%5Bterms%5D=&amp;range=&amp;collection=24&amp;type=&amp;user=&amp;tags=&amp;public=&amp;featured=&amp;exhibit=&amp;submit_search=Search+for+items\" target=\"_blank\">letters referenced by other letters</a>.</p>',1),(8,21,'file-text','{\"file-position\":\"left\"}','<p>this is a test</p>',1),(9,23,'text',NULL,'<div id=\"LGBT\">&nbsp;</div>',1),(10,25,'file-text','{\"file-position\":\"left\"}','<div class=\"wrap\">\r\n<div class=\"content\">\r\n<div class=\"dd\">\r\n<p>Jeffrey T. Wilson was born in Portsmouth, Virginia, in 1843. There is uncertainty about the ownership of his mother at the time of his birth and conflicting accounts, but Wilson appears to have been owned by the Charles A. Grice family, who he lived with beginning in 1853. Prior to then, he was living with his mother and stepfather (Moses Taylor?). According to his obituary, he learned to read and write in secret. Based on his diary, he was the body servant of A[lexnander]. P. Grice, likely the son of his owner, who served with Company A, Cohoon\'s Battalion, Virginia Infantry, at least during a part of 1862. In 1866, after being freed, Wilson enlisted and went to Europe with the U.S. Navy. When he returned home, he lived in the house he inherited from his mother. Wilson worked at the Portsmouth Navy Yard, as a laborer, and as a bailiff for the Federal Court at Norfolk. In his later years, from 1924 until his death in 1929, he wrote a column called \"Colored Notes\" for&nbsp;<em>The Portsmouth Star</em>. The column included social news, Wilson\'s political views, and issues of race relations--all themes that occur throughout his diaries. Wilson was active in the Emmanuel AME Church in Portsmouth, where he taught Sunday school. In June of 1929, Wilson was hit by a car. He died at his son\'s home, two months later, on August 25, 1929.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>',1),(11,26,'file-text','{\"file-position\":\"right\"}','<p align=\"center\"><strong>&ldquo;</strong><em>For over two hundred years we suffered the horrors slavery. in this and other countries. and. </em><em>why?.&rdquo;&nbsp;</em><sup>1</sup></p>\r\n<p>Wilson was born on May 10<sup>th</sup>, 1843 &ldquo;in &lsquo;slave quarters,&rsquo;&hellip; on the north side of South street, just east of Court Street&rdquo; in Portsmouth, Virginia.<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;Under &lsquo;the peculiar system&rsquo; of the 19<sup>th</sup> century, Wilson&rsquo;s mother belonged to Eliza T. Edwards, who was the wife of &ldquo;one of Portsmouth&rsquo;s wealthiest citizens.&rdquo;<sup>&nbsp;3</sup>&nbsp;After the death of her first husband Edwards married Charles A. Grice. Wilson thus became the chattel property of the Grice family, whom Wilson served throughout the war.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wilson was little more than ten years old when Grice took him from his mother. &ldquo;<em>This day 60 years ago [1853], the writer was a little slave boy living on Bermuda [S]treet in Norfolk with my dear mother and wicked stepfather, he was a hackman, and my mother was a laundress. &mdash;It was from there a year or two later, that old man C[harles].A. Grice, and his wife [Eliza T. Grice] came and arbitrarily carried me back to Portsmouth and put me to work and put me at work in the garden, planting Irish Potatoes&hellip; I learned then that I was a slave [sic].&rdquo;</em> (Aug. 14)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The very nature of the slave system was coercive, and its abuses were socially pervasive. Escaping slavery through legal and illegal means required persistence and daring on the part of the enslaved. Under the law slaves were not allowed to testify against whites in court. As a result proving crimes committed against/upon them by whites was next to imposable, even with the assistance of sympathetic whites. Outthinking predatory whites was thus an integral part of survival within and resistance to the slavery system. In slave narratives such stories take on special significance because they represent small victories over the system displaying daring and mental faculties, which were consistently denied by slavers. On July 26<sup>th</sup>, Wilson recounts such a story about his mother:</p>\r\n<p><em>Fifty seven years ago [1856]. my dear old Mother. outwitted J.M. Rellen and Frank Pierce. h[e]</em><em>&nbsp;old Rellen had done sneaked in. and had my stepfather put in jail. Came back and did the same to&nbsp; mother. they then searched the house for the old folks money. Which they had. but Rellen and Pierce. never found it. mother had secured it so. that they couldn&rsquo;t. and that same money $700.<sup>00</sup> I think. in&nbsp; gold and silver. was used to buy my stepfathers freedom[.] </em>(Jul. 26<sup>th</sup> 278)*</p>\r\n<p>Buying one&rsquo;s freedom was just one way of escaping slavery.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Just a year later the Yellow Fever epidemic of 1855 swept through Portsmouth and Norfolk. Wilson&rsquo;s older brother John seized the opportunity.<em>&ldquo;Fifty eight years ago [1855] my brother John and me walked down to the ferry landing in Norfolk, and he got into a boat, and boarded a vessel lying in the stream, loaded for Boston, and made good his escape&hellip;That was what termed U.G.R.R. [Underground Rail Road]&rdquo;</em> (Aug. 14). Wilson wouldn&rsquo;t see his brother again until after the war.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; John&rsquo;s escape during the 1855 epidemic was anything but coincidental. In another/a different entry Wilson writes: &ldquo;<em>Fifty eight years ago this month [August] the great epidemic. Yellow Fever. Was raging in Portsmouth and Norfolk. White people were dying by scores, and a very few colored.&rdquo;</em> (Aug. 12). Yellow Fever is believed to have originated in Africa. Thus Africa Americans processed greater immunity to the disease compared to Europeans American. John Wilson was no doubt not the only person to take advantage of his genetic inherence to escape bondage during this period. &ldquo;<em>The Yellow fever was so serious, White people had no time to look after runaway Negroes but after the dying whites.&rdquo;</em> (Aug. 14)</p>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;As might be expected the indignities of slavery became progressively worse as Wilson got older. Three years after the epidemic, Wilson recounts:&nbsp;&ldquo;<em>I was hired out for the first time in my life, and F[rancis].W. Lemosy was my new master, he was mean, his wife was meaner, the children were the same. The mulatto nurse and the [I]rish cook was no better..</em>. <em>They gave me stale victuals worked me hard in the garden&hellip;</em> <em>[I?] had to rise before day and got cuffs and kicks if I didn&rsquo;t</em>.&rdquo; (Jan 1).Wilson&rsquo;s poor treatment at the Lemosy house, in his own words, &ldquo;<em>caused me to do what I would not have done had I realized the enormity of it, to get clear of them [i.e. ran away].&rdquo;&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p>\"Every white person I lived with or served, as a slave 60 years ago and less have long since gone the way of all the earth ie &ldquo;They have slumbered for years in their graves.&rdquo;&nbsp;(Sept. 16)</p>\r\n<p>\"The [S]outh lost out in their fight 50 years ago on the battle field for a separate government. Whose cornerstone would be Negro slavery, but have regained more than they lost in the half of the Congress i.e. absolute control of the [E]xecutive, also and us. We are the persecuted. Worse than the Israel[ites] in Egypt in the a sense and Why are <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">We</span>? &hellip;Why?\" (Aug. 2)&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>_______________</div>\r\n<div><ol>\r\n<li>Jeffrey T. Wilson,&nbsp;<em>1913 Diary.</em>June 22</li>\r\n<li><em>Portsmouth Star&nbsp;</em>Obituery of Wilson</li>\r\n<li>Wilson&rsquo;s mother&rsquo;s name has not been recorded by Wilson or other sources.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol></div>',1),(12,27,'file-text','{\"file-position\":\"right\"}','<p style=\"text-align: left;\" align=\"center\">Wilson was eighteen, before Virginia succeed from the Union in 1861. At the opening of the war, Wilson found himself in the Confederate capital.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Fifty two years ago this country was stirred by a cruel war between the states, and the south said they would soon drive the &ldquo;Yankees&rdquo; back and have a confederacy whose bedrock would be Negro slavery. but God. Who is greater than man decreed otherwise., and they were taught a lesson Which will not be forgotten. &ldquo;tho&rdquo; they may try to forget. They may have their re-unions etc. recount their deeds of valor in a lost cause, nevertheless, the lesson stanfs stands and looms once in a while and whispers. &ldquo;What fools these mortals are&rdquo;&nbsp; (Jul. 20<sup>th</sup>)</p>\r\n<p>Fifty two years ago the battle of Bull [R]un or 1<sup>st</sup> Manassas was fought. and Yanks &ldquo;skedaddled&rdquo; to Washington. to my regret. &mdash;There were about 500 prisoners brought back to Richmond. Where I lived being hired out slave boy. at the corner of Franklin and 17<sup>th</sup> sts. to Dr. J.W. Garlick a fairly kind man, he died the next year. The confed[erate]s were in high feather over their victory and if they had pushed it. the result of the Civil War would have been entirely different. but they did not see their opportunity and God be praised for it (Jul. 22)</p>\r\n<p>This day 50 years ago I was a forced refugee from here living in N.C.&nbsp; &mdash; The Civil War was in progress and our Confederates were correspondingly depressed. Lee had been defeated at Gettysburg, and the backbone of the rebellion broken. Yet it waged near two years longer against fearful odds.. (Aug. 12 296)</p>\r\n<p>This day 50 years ago I was a slave of Geo W. Grice living temporarily-from a military, standpoint-at company shop N.C. R.R. Alamance Co N.C.&mdash; (Aug. 30<sup>th</sup>)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>________________</p>',1),(13,28,'file-text','{\"file-position\":\"right\"}','<p>A year after Lee&rsquo;s surrender, and Lincoln&rsquo;s assassination, then Democratic president Andrew Johnson vetoed Congress&rsquo;s extension of the Freedmen&rsquo;s Bureau and then the Civil Rights Bill. A two-thirds majority in Congress overruled him. Former bondsmen where over joyed. On April 2<sup>nd </sup>Wilson recalled that:</p>\r\n<p>Forty-seven years ago [1866] the colored folks of Norfolk and Portsmouth celebrated the passage of the \"Civil Rights Bill\" by Congress and we all gathered in the city of Norfolk [and we] had a big parade of civic societies, and discharge colored soldiers speaking out on the suburbs. The poor whites \"sicked [sic] on\" doubtless, by the upper class, interfered with us. [They] tried to break us up. [A] riot ensued and several whites were killed. I was unhurt. Who killed the parties was never known, but several colored men left the city for fear of arrest, and have never returned.<sup>13</sup></p>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Writing of the Norfolk riot, decades later, historian Alrutheus Ambush Taylor, stated that on April 16, 1866&mdash;the date in question&mdash;African American residents celebrating the passage of the of the Civil Rights Bill were fired on as their procession passed the house of Mrs. Whitehurst.<sup>14</sup> &ldquo;There followed a general m&ecirc;l&eacute;e in which it was reported that two blacks and two whites were killed and several others injured. A military force was required to disperse the mob.&rdquo;<sup>15</sup></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The racial violence Wilson, and Taylor, describe in Norfolk was in no way an isolated incident. Following the turmoil of 1866, &ldquo;northern voters returned a huge Republican Party majority to Congress.&rdquo;<sup>16</sup> The following spring, &ldquo;emboldened&nbsp;Republicans passed a series of Reconstruction Acts that returned former Confederate States to military rule&rdquo; and call for elections for new state constitutional conventions.<sup>17 </sup>Virginia became Military District Number One.<sup>18</sup> In the spring of 1867, Virginians began the task of rebuilding their state government. Once again Wilson found himself at the epicenter of events.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On April 30<sup>th</sup>, Wilson wrote: &ldquo;This month... I was a delegate from our home city [Portsmouth, Virginia]. Forty-six years ago [1867] to the first republican state convention. Which met in Richmond in the first Baptist Church. It was &ldquo;thru&rdquo; the influence of late Geo[rge] Teamoh that I went<em>&rdquo;<sup>19</sup>&nbsp;&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p><em>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</em>As a delegate, Wilson was instrumental in the nomination of a number of African American candidates, including his friend George Teamoh, who went on to the Virginia Constitutional Convention later that year.<sup>20</sup> According to the Virginia General Assembly website, George Teamoh was &ldquo;born a slave in Portsmouth in 1818, was a carpenter [and an] accomplished public speaker&hellip; [He] served in the Senate of Virginia from 1869 to 1871... [H]e was denied re-nomination to the Senate of Virginia in 1871, due to party factionalism, and ran unsuccessfully for the Virginia House of Delegates. He was an advocate of African American self-help, was a founder of Portsmouth&rsquo;s first African American school, and was active in African Methodist Episcopal (A.M.E.) church affairs in the city.&rdquo;<sup>21</sup>Which is where the two men most likely meet.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wilson&rsquo;s recollections of Reconstruction were not nearly as rosy as his contemporary John R. Lynch.<sup>22</sup> On May 22<sup>nd</sup> Wilson wrote:</p>\r\n<p><em>Forty-two years ago [1870] on or about this date there was an election riot between whites and blacks&hellip; Moses Scott who shot a white man had to flee in the night how he got out of the city I never have learned but he went to Boston Mass. He never returned. He died in that city, and I learned he lost his reason.&rdquo; </em></p>\r\n<p>Perhaps discouraged by the riot Wilson stated that he cast his firstvote a year later &ldquo;in Norfolk County [and that] several colored men were on the ticket and they are all gone &ldquo;the way of the earth.<sup>23&nbsp;</sup></p>\r\n<hr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n<div><ol>\r\n<li>Wilson,&ldquo;Wanamaker diary,&rdquo; 212.</li>\r\n<li>Charles E. Wynes, <em>Race Relations in Virginia 1870-1902 </em>(University of</li>\r\n<li>Virginia Press, 1961) 10.</li>\r\n<li>Sometimes referred to as &lsquo;Black Codes.&rsquo;</li>\r\n</ol></div>\r\n</div>',1),(14,29,'file-text','{\"file-position\":\"right\"}','<p>In a tragic reversal of fate, between 1867 and 1871, African Americans lost significant representation in the Virginia General Assembly. Historian Charles E. Wynes, in his book <em>Race Relations in Virginia 1870-1902</em>, details the political turnabout of 1871: &ldquo;From twenty-one Negro members in the House, the number was reduced to fourteen. In the Senate, Negro membership was halved, from six to three&hellip; The attrition of every election steadily reduced Negro membership in the General Assembly, till finally, in 1891, the Negro no longer sat in the nation&rsquo;s oldest, representative, legislative assembly.&rdquo;<sup>1</sup> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Wilson is strangely silent regarding the years that followed. We know that the 1877 Compromise, which lead to the withdrawal of Northern troops from the Southern States, as well economic downturn of the late 1800s greatly undermined the political power of Radical Republicans. Between 1877 and 1913 Conservative politicians (who referred to themselves as &lsquo;Redeemers&rsquo;) worked steadily to disenfranchise black voters through extensive &lsquo;election reforms.&rsquo;<sup>2</sup></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By the early 19<sup>th</sup> century the political landscape of the United States had changed substantially. Roosevelt&rsquo;s efforts to establish a Progressive Party in the United States culminated in the division of Republican voters on November 5<sup>th</sup> 1912. The division of this once powerful voting block provided for the unexpected victory of the Democratic candidate, and Staunton native, Woodrow-Wilson.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On Aug. 2<sup>nd </sup>1913,just six months after Woodrow-Wilson assume office, Wilson wrote bitterly: &ldquo;The [S]outh lost out in their fight 50 years ago on the battle field for a separate government. Whose cornerstone would be Negro slavery, but have regained more than they lost in the half of the Congress i.e. absolute control of the [E]xecutive, also and us. We are the persecuted. Worse than [the Israelites] in Egypt.&rdquo;<a title=\"August 2nd Con.\" href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/files/show/4180\" target=\"_blank\"><sup>3</sup></a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In his first year in office, Wilson pursued an ambitious political agenda that all but ignored African Americans living in the United States. On Aug. 29<sup>th</sup> 1913, Wilson wrote: &ldquo;This is a test of the democratic party. They say or said that they are our best friends. Well if such is true, Good Lord, save us from our friends. But it serves us right. Our people ought to have stood by the party and not Roosevelt.&rdquo;<sup>27 </sup>Wilson&rsquo;s misgivings about the new president would&mdash;sadly&mdash;be substantiated in the months that followed. Woodrow-Wilson&rsquo;s southern sympathies enabled states and municipalities to move forward rapidly on comprehensive segregation legislation, which would come to be known collectively as Jim Crow.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That there were relatively few segregation ordinances before the nineteen-teens does not imply that segregation was altogether new. The idea of segregation had taken root in the minds of many lower and middleclass whites around the turn of the century. Over that time communities became increasingly divided, both economically and racially. On June 24<sup>th</sup>, Wilson observed: &ldquo;Negroes at one time resided on every street this side of So[uth] Portsmouth but now there is practically a very few east of Green [Street], if I except East Glasgow, Columbia and Bart. Yes King, it is Segregation without law.&rdquo;<sup>28 &nbsp;</sup></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Interestingly enough, the very first segregation ordinances appeared in Baltimore, Maryland.<sup>29</sup> In an ironic twist of fate, the state that famously abolished slavery in 1864 became the first to condone the legally segregate her residents. In the <em>Journal of Southern History,</em> Roger L. Rice writes that from 1910 &ldquo;[t]he flame kindled in Baltimore began to spread. In the spring of 1911 Richmond, Virginia, passed a segregation ordinance [,] which was later declared valid in the state supreme court. From this time until 1913 a number of other cities adopted residential segregation statues. &rdquo;<sup>30</sup> In his book <em>As Long As They Don&rsquo;t Move Next Door,</em> Virginia resident and historian Stephen Grant Meyer states that &ldquo;[i]n 1912, Virginia enacted legislation giving communities the right to restrict neighborhoods.&rdquo;<sup>31 </sup>And a year later, cities such as Ashland, Norfolk, Portsmouth, and Roanoke had passed their own ordinances. On Sept. 24<sup>th </sup>1913, Wilson wrote despondently: &ldquo;The democratic council has passed the segregation ordinance. I wonder if C.W. Walker will segregate the negroes&rsquo; laundry? He is in the laundry business, he will never segregate mine.&rdquo;<sup>32</sup><a title=\"\" href=\"#_ftn2\"><br /></a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;As an old man it was beyond Wilson&rsquo;s abilities to turn the tide of segregation, so he unwillingly resigned himself to it. Following his reflection on the Republican Convention 1867, Wilson wrote: &ldquo;It is a common expression that majorities rule. [Today] we have a president [Woodrow-Wilson] and congress [63<sup>rd</sup>] who represents a minority, but it is the law, and we have to submit to it, but it not only so in that case. But every southern state is dominated by a bourbon minority.&rdquo;<sup>33</sup></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In his melancholy Wilson did not spare his own people from a share in the shame of segregation. Writing of the Emancipation Proclamation, on Sept. 8<sup>th</sup> Wilson stated &ldquo;Fifty years ago [1863] was the Negros opportunity but he let it slip. &mdash;There have been numerous other opportunities since, nipped in the bud and both are gone<em>.</em>&rdquo;<sup>34</sup>To Wilson the promise of equality had been tangible&mdash;if fleeting&mdash;and his sense of loss was immense.</p>\r\n<p><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </em>&nbsp;Jeffrey T. Wilson would not live to see what C. Vann Woodward termed the &lsquo;Second Reconstruction&rsquo; and what we know today as the Civil Right Movement. In 1929, Wilson was struck, while walking in the street, by an automobile and died.<sup>35</sup>&nbsp;The writings he left behind reveal his own personal struggle to assume basic dignities and political rights in the years following the Civil War. His thoughts and feelings speak to the trials and triumphs of those lost between slavery and Civil Rights. Therefore the Wanamaker Diary serves to illuminate the experiences of African Americans struggling in the historic darkness of Jim Crow.</p>\r\n<p>____________________</p>\r\n<div><ol>\r\n<li>Charles E. Wynes.&nbsp;<em>Race Relations in Virginia 1870-1902&nbsp;</em>(University of Virginia Press, 1961) 10.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a title=\"Aug. 2nd Con\" href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/files/show/4180\" target=\"_blank\">Wilson, &ldquo;Wanamaker diary&rdquo; 286. </a>Wilson&rsquo;s diary abounds with biblical&nbsp;analogies of this nature.</li>\r\n<li>Ibid. 314.</li>\r\n<li>Ibid. 246.</li>\r\n<li>C. Vann Woodward, <em>The Strange Career of Jim Crow</em> (New York: Oxford</li>\r\n<li>Press, 1974) 100.</li>\r\n<li>Roger L. Rice<em>, &ldquo;</em>Residential Segregation by Law, 1910-1917&rdquo;<em> Journal of</em></li>\r\n<li><em>Southern History </em>Vol. 34, No. 2 (May, 1968) pp. 179-199. http://www.jstor.org/stable/2204656</li>\r\n<li>StephenGrant Meyer, <em>As Long As They Don&rsquo;t Move Next Door: Segregation</em></li>\r\n<li><em>and Racial Conflict in American Neighborhood:&nbsp; </em>(Lanham: Rowman &amp; Littlefield Publishers Inc. 2000) 20.</li>\r\n<li>Wilson,&ldquo;Wanamaker diary&rdquo; 341. The quip about the laundry mostly likely refers</li>\r\n<li>to the custom of hiring out laundry to African American women.</li>\r\n<li>Ibid. 190</li>\r\n<li>Ibid. 324</li>\r\n<li><a title=\"Obituary\" href=\"http://racetimeplace.com/497Projects/2003students/carlos/JTWObit.htm\">Wilson&rsquo;s Obituary published in <em>The Portsmouth Star</em>.</a></li>\r\n</ol></div>',1),(15,30,'text',NULL,'<p><strong>1843</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Born</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1855</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>1855 Yellow fever/Jonh Wilson=U.G.R.R. &nbsp;<a title=\"Aug. 12 Con\" href=\"https://omeka.lib.vt.edu/files/show/4185\">296</a>/298/302&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1856</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Buying his stepfathers freedom 278</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1858</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hired out 70</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1861</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Battle of Bull Run, Richmond Va.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1862</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>May jail Richmond 19y. 210</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;body servant for A. P. Grice. who was an officer in Cohoon\'s Battalion C.S.A. encamped on \"Dunn\'s Hill,\" near Petersburg.</li>\r\n<li>Jan. Monroe VA against my will, but I was contented.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1863</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Feb. Exchange hotel &amp; Ballard House Richmond. 127</li>\r\n<li>Alamance Co. NC. N.C.R.R. 314</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;.324</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1864</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>March to the Sea 388</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1866</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Civil Rights bill .162</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1867&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Annapolis MD</li>\r\n<li>Cherbourg France .272&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1868</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Delegate R convention 190</li>\r\n<li>U.S. Navy = Cuban</li>\r\n<li>June 9 discharged Navy .230</li>\r\n<li>Judge John C. Underwood was US. District Court for this district, and the leading spirit in framing the now defunct constitution of Va .310</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1870</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>married to Imogene 73 first child 354 (1871?).</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;Samuel Davis elected to city council</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1871</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Election riot 212</li>\r\n<li>Black police officer .274(1873?)&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1872</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>first vote 212</li>\r\n<li>Emily 1<sup>st</sup> daughter 310</li>\r\n<li>revival Immanuel 324 conversion 357</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1873</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>member of the City Council 342</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1877</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>&ldquo;military company&rdquo;</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;son Allen is born 78</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1874</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Navy Yard-1884 304</li>\r\n<li>becomes SS leader 178&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1876</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>the Virginia Guards. the first militia company ever organized in the city. was mustered in by Capt John Gibson, Jas. E. Manning was Captain. I was 1<sup>st</sup> Lieut. and Geo W. Gordon, was 2<sup>nd</sup>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;1881</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>R.G.L Paige, was assistant postmaster at Norfolk, and Capt. John Gibson, was delivery clerk, both of them were colored 348</li>\r\n<li>Daughter Mary Emily Ophelia dies age 9.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1888</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>John C. Asbury, was commonwealth atty. of Norfolk County the only colored man that have ever held it. 304</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;1889</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mother dies 246</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1893</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>ran for election 246</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1910</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Son Jeffery Wilson Jr. moves to CA</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1911</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Blanch arrives in Norfolk they are married 3 days later&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1912</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Wendell Wilson is born.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1913</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sept 23 &ldquo;Educational Congress&rdquo;</li>\r\n<li>Sept 24 segregation ordinance</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1924&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Wilson begins opinion column for the <em>Portsmouth Star.&nbsp;</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>1929</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Wilson is struck by a car</li>\r\n<li>Wilson dies Aug. 29th 1929&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>',1),(16,31,'text',NULL,'<p><a title=\"Jeffrey T. Wilson Colored Notes \" href=\"http://racetimeplace.com/497Projects/2003students/carlos/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Jeffrey T. Wilson Colored Notes</a></p>\r\n<p>Undergraduate historcial research conducted on Wilson\'s column in <em>the Portsmouth Star.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<p><a title=\"Africa American Historical Society of Portsmoth\" href=\"http://www.blackhistoryportsmouth.org/\" target=\"_blank\">The African American Historical Society of Portsmouth</a></p>\r\n<p>The organization is dedicated to collecting local African history and promoting, encouraging, and coordinating original historical activities, relating to African Americans in the Portsmouth area through oral and written interviews and other research activities. The organization is also interested in identifying locations and owners of African American artifacts, pictures and/or photographs and other objects.</p>\r\n<p><a title=\"Emanuel A.M.E\" href=\"http://racetimeplace.com/taleoftwochurches/index.html\" target=\"_blank\"><em><br /></em>A Tale of Two Churches: Emanuel A.M.E., Monumental Methodist, and the Underground Railroad in Portsmouth, Virginia.&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n<p>In 2003, Norfolk State University professors Cassandra Newby Alexander, William Alexander, and Jeffrey Littlejohn launched a study of the Underground Railroad (URR) in Portsmouth, Virginia. With a supporting crew of local historians, including Mae Breckenridge-Haywood, Margaret Windley, and Sheldon Collins, the Norfolk State team focused its attention on the historical area in downtown Portsmouth. Two churches -- Emanuel A.M.E. and Monumental Methodist -- were the initial sites of investigation. Portsmouth\'s oral-history tradition held that members of these churches aided enslaved African Americans, who were \"secreted out\" of the city on ships bound for the North.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',1),(17,32,'file-text','{\"file-position\":\"left\"}','<p>The Virginia Tech LGBTQ Oral History Project had its beginnings in the Ex Lapide Society members&rsquo; concern with documenting their history. Latanya Walker, Director of Alumni Relations for Diversity, Inclusion and Community Engagement, facilitated early meetings on discovering this history. In fall 2014, David Cline, Assistant Professor of History and Director of the Graduate Certificate in Public History, taught two courses, Introduction to Oral History (undergraduate) and Oral History: Methods, Theories, and Practice (graduate), both of them focused on LGBTQ history in the South. As part of these classes, students conducted 18 original oral history interviews with Virginia Tech faculty, staff, students, and alumni. Dr. Cline and University Archivist Tamara Kennelly also conducted oral history interviews and they, as well as several of Dr. Cline&rsquo;s graduate and undergraduate students, are continuing to interview through spring 2015. Dr. Cline&rsquo;s fall 2015 undergraduate class, Introduction to Oral History, will again focus on LGBTQ Southern/VT history and will again conduct oral history interviews. Jean Elliott, Communications Director for the College of Liberal Arts and Science; Sharon Leon, Director of Public Projects at Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media and Associate Professor of History at George Mason University; and Mark Weber, class of 1987, are on the project&rsquo;s advisory board. Kennelly is Project Coordinator. The Omeka timeline and website was designed by Adrienne Serra, Technical Archivist in Special Collections.</p>\r\n<p>If you have materials to donate, please contact University Archivist Tamara Kennelly (<a href=\"mailto:tjk@vt.edu\">tjk@vt.edu</a>). Materials will be made available through the reading room of the Special Collections Department of the University Libraries, which is located on the first floor of Newman Library.</p>',1);
